Effect.die takes a value and throws it as an unchecked defect, producing Effect<never, never, never>. Effect.orDie converts an existing typed failure channel into a defect — useful when you decide a particular error should be fatal. Both move the failure out of the E channel into the unrecoverable defect channel, where only Effect.catchAllDefect (not catchAll) can observe it.

```typescript
import { Effect, Data, pipe } from "effect";

class ParseError extends Data.TaggedError("ParseError")<{ readonly input: string }> {}

const parse = (s: string): Effect.Effect<number, ParseError> =>
  Number.isFinite(Number(s)) ? Effect.succeed(Number(s)) : Effect.fail(new ParseError({ input: s }));

// orDie: typed failure becomes a defect
export const mustParse = (s: string): Effect.Effect<number> =>
  pipe(parse(s), Effect.orDie);

// die directly: explicit fatal shutdown
export const explode: Effect.Effect<never> = Effect.die(new Error("unreachable invariant broken"));
```

