Effect.promise assumes the Promise will never reject; any rejection becomes an unchecked defect. Effect.tryPromise asks for a catch function that narrows unknown to a typed error, keeping failures in the E channel so callers must handle them. Use Effect.promise for Promises you control (constants, already-resolved values); use Effect.tryPromise for anything talking to the outside world.

```typescript
